 of her friend Julia Child, the cook just down the block in Cambridge, White surmounted unforeseen obstacles and epic-sized crises in the kitchen, along the way developing the surefire strategies described here. All of these recipes can be prepared in your kitchen using ordinary pots, pans, and utensils. For each tantalizing recipe, White gives portions for serving groups of six, twelve, twenty, and fifty. Featuring a lively new introduction by White and Edward Koren's charming illustrations, Cooking for Crowds offers simple, step-by-step instructions for easy cooking and entertaining on a grand scale--from hors d'oeuvres to desserts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternational cooking. 0aQuantity cooking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aAllspice.  aBaking.  aBaklava.  aBay leaf.  aBeef.  aBlack pepper.  aBoiling.  aBorscht.  aBread.  aBroth.  aCabbage.  aCaraway.  aCasserole.  aCatering.  aCheesecloth.  aChili con carne.  aChili pepper.  aChili powder.  aChives.  aCookbook.  aCooking.  aCoriander.  aCorn on the cob.  aCouscous.  aCream.  aCucumber raita.  aCumin.  aCurry.  aDessert.  aDill.  aDinner.  aDough.  aDumpling.  aFlour.  aFried egg.  aFrying pan.  aGarlic.  aGarnish (food).  aGreen pepper.  aGround (electricity).  aGround meat.  aHarissa.  aHerb.  aIngredient.  aJiaozi.  aJulia Child.  aLadyfinger (biscuit).  aLemon.  aLentil.  aLettuce.  aLoaf.  aLunch.  aMargarine.  aMayonnaise.  aMeal.  aMeat.  aMeatball.  aMoussaka.  aNoodle.  aOlive oil.  aOnion ring.  aOven.  aParsley.  aPastry.  aPesto.  aPlum tomato.  aPork.  aPrune.  aPumpernickel.  aPurée.  aQuantity.  aRaita.  